Unsupervised Learning Project: AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on Unsupervised Learning. We will be using Credit Card Customer Data for this project.

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers.

Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers' queries are resolved faster. The head of marketing and the head of delivery, both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective¶

Identify different segments in the existing customer base, taking into account their spending patterns as well as past interactions with the bank.

About the data¶

Data is available on customers of the bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which the customer has contacted the bank for any queries. These different channels include visiting the bank, online, and through a call center.

  • Sl_no - Customer Serial Number
  • Customer Key - Customer identification
  • Avg_Credit_Limit - Average credit limit (currency is not specified, you can make an assumption around this)
  • Total_Credit_Cards - Total number of credit cards
  • Total_visits_bank - Total bank visits
  • Total_visits_online - Total online visits
  • Total_calls_made - Total calls made

Observation:¶

Duplicate Customer Keys:

There are 660 total rows in your dataset, but only 655 unique customer keys. This means that 5 customer keys are duplicated (i.e., there are multiple rows for these customers).

Many reasons for duplication can be as follows:

  • Multiple Interactions: Customers could have had multiple interactions with the bank (different visits, calls, or transactions) over time, leading to multiple records.

  • Data Entry Issues: There could be inconsistencies in how customer data is recorded, leading to duplicate entries.

  • Partial Data: Some duplicates might be partial (i.e., some columns have identical data, while others differ).

  • Data Aggregation Problem: If the dataset was collected from multiple sources (e.g., call center, online banking), some customers may have been recorded more than once.

We will Rectify the Issue of the Duplicate Customer Keys, as its a critical columns and it could hinder analysis if not handled properly.

Observation from the Duplicate Customer Key Analysis:

  • None of the rows with duplicate customer keys are completely identical, so there is no need to drop or delete any data points or rows.
  • The differences in duplicate records are primarily related to the number of credit cards, total visits to the bank, calls to customer care, or online visits related to bank transactions. To address this, I will aggregate the data for these customers.
  • Aggregating the data will allow us to consolidate customer information. For example, summing the visits for customers who have multiple records will give us a complete view of their total interactions with the bank. Similarly, averaging the credit limit will provide a more accurate estimate of the customer’s overall financial standing.

# Aggregating data for duplicate customer keys
df_aggregated = df.groupby('Customer Key').agg({
    'Avg_Credit_Limit': 'mean',         # Take average of credit limits
    'Total_Credit_Cards': 'mean',       # Take average of credit cards
    'Total_visits_bank': 'sum',         # Sum bank visits
    'Total_visits_online': 'sum',       # Sum online visits

# For the distribution and outliers we will look for each variable in the data, we will utilize box plots and histograms to visualize key numerical data.

# Function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize = (12, 7), kde = False, bins = None):
    
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12, 7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows = 2,      # Number of rows of the subplot grid = 2
        sharex = True,  # X-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize = figsize,
    )  # Creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data = data, x = feature, ax = ax_box2, showmeans = True, color = "violet"
    )  # Boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2, bins = bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data = data, x = feature, kde = kde, ax = ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color = "green", linestyle = "--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color = "black", linestyle = "-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Key Insights:

                    There is a strong negative correlation between total credit cards and total calls made. This suggests that customers with more credit cards tend to make fewer calls, possibly because they are more self-sufficient or use other channels like online services.

  • Total_visits_bank: There is a strong negative correlation between bank visits and online visits, indicating that customers who visit the bank frequently tend to use online services less.

  • Total_calls_made: Customers who make more calls tend to have lower credit limits and fewer credit cards. Customers who make more calls are less likely to visit the bank in person, likely indicating that they prefer resolving issues via phone.

Summary:

Higher credit limits are associated with more credit cards and more online engagement but fewer calls to customer support.

Customers who make more bank visits tend to make fewer online visits and fewer calls, possibly indicating a preference for in-person interactions.

Customers with more credit cards tend to make fewer calls and may rely on online services more frequently.

These insights can help the bank identify customer behavior patterns, inform strategies for improving customer service, and tailor marketing campaigns to different segments based on their engagement with the bank.

Observation:

  • The transformed scaled PCA data represents the first six principal components (PC1 to PC6) after applying Principal Component Analysis (PCA) on the scaled dataset.

  • Each row corresponds to a data point (a customer, for example), and each column represents one of the principal components (PC1 to PC6). The values in each cell represent the projection of that data point on the corresponding principal component axis.

  • PC1, PC2, PC3, etc. are the new axes created by PCA. These axes are linear combinations of the original features and are ordered in terms of the amount of variance they explain. PC1 explains the most variance in the dataset, followed by PC2, and so on.

For instance, data points with a high positive or negative value in PC1 indicate that those points contribute significantly to the most important direction of variance in your dataset.

We can also visualize the data in 2 dimensions, using the first two principal components.

K-Means¶

Let us now fit the K-means algorithm on our pca components and find out the optimum number of clusters to use.

We will do this in 3 steps:

  1. Initialize a dictionary to store the Sum of Squared Error (SSE) for each K
  2. Run for a range of Ks and store SSE for each run
  3. Plot the SSE vs K and plot the elbow curve

K-Means clustering is one of the most popular clustering algorithms used for partitioning a dataset into K clusters. The algorithm works by iteratively assigning each data point to one of the K clusters based on the proximity of the data points to the centroids of the clusters. K-Means clustering is a computationally efficient algorithm that can work well even for datasets with a large number of variables.

The steps involved in K-Means clustering are as follows:

Choose the number of clusters K that you want to partition the data into.

Initialize the K centroids randomly.

Assign each data point to the nearest centroid.

Recalculate the centroids of each cluster as the mean of all the data points assigned to it.

Repeat steps 3 and 4 until the centroids no longer change or a maximum number of iterations is reached.

In [ ]:
# Empty dictionary to store the SSE for each value of K
sse = {} 

# Iterate for a range of Ks and fit the scaled data to the algorithm. 
# Use inertia attribute from the clustering object and store the inertia value for that K 
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 1).fit(data_pca)
    
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_

# Elbow plot
plt.figure()

plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values()), 'bx-')

plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")

plt.ylabel("SSE")

plt.show()

Observations:

  • From the plot, you can see that the SSE decreases sharply between 1 and 4 clusters, but after 4, the rate of decrease slows down.

  • The elbow is typically at the point where the line starts to bend and flatten out. In this plot, the elbow appears to be around k = 4. After this point, adding more clusters does not significantly reduce the SSE.

Gaussian Mixture Model¶

The Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) is a clustering method that groups data by assuming each cluster follows a bell-shaped curve (Gaussian distribution). Unlike K-Means, it assigns data points to clusters based on probabilities, allowing for more flexible and overlapping clusters.

Let's now create clusters using the Gaussian Mixture Model.

In [ ]:

Key Observations for K-Means and GMM Clustering Visualization

  • Cluster Separation:

In K-Means, the clusters are more distinctly separated due to the hard assignment of points to a cluster. In GMM, there is more overlap, especially between Clusters 0 and 1 (orange and green in GMM), which shows that GMM allows for probabilistic membership, meaning some points have a high likelihood of belonging to multiple clusters.

  • Cluster Shape:

K-Means forces the clusters to be spherical, which works well when the underlying clusters have clear boundaries. GMM provides more flexibility by allowing the clusters to take different shapes, especially where there is more uncertainty or overlap in the data (as seen between orange and green clusters in GMM).

  • Outliers:

In both visualizations, some outliers can be seen, particularly in Cluster 1 (blue) for K-Means and Cluster 2 (blue) for GMM. This suggests that both algorithms capture the bulk of the clusters well but may handle extreme values or outliers differently.

  • Interpretation:

K-Means seems to work well for distinct, well-separated clusters (like Cluster 2 in green) but might struggle where there is ambiguity (as seen in the overlap between Clusters 0 and 3). GMM captures uncertainty better in overlapping areas by assigning probabilities, which explains why clusters are less strictly separated. This might provide better insight into data points that belong to multiple groupings.

Conclusion:

K-Means is a good choice for scenarios where strict, non-overlapping clusters are needed.

GMM provides more flexibility by accounting for uncertainty in cluster assignment, which might be better for data with overlap or less distinct boundaries.

Both algorithms provide valuable insights, and the choice depends on whether you prioritize strict separation or probabilistic assignments in your clustering task.

Comparing Clusters:¶

Interpretation After Comparing K-Means and GMM Clustering:¶

1. Cluster Sizes:

  • K-Means produced clusters of relatively equal sizes, which is a hallmark of the algorithm’s tendency to create balanced clusters. This can be useful when you want clusters to have similar amounts of data points.

  • GMM, however, allowed for more imbalanced clusters, where one cluster might have more or fewer points than another due to the algorithm’s probabilistic nature. For example, Cluster 3 in GMM might capture a smaller number of high-value customers, while Cluster 0 in K-Means could represent a larger group of moderate-value customers.

    Conclusion: K-Means tends to produce more balanced clusters, while GMM creates clusters based on the underlying structure of the data, even if that results in some clusters being larger or smaller.

    2. Cross-Tabulation:

  • The cross-tabulation shows a strong alignment between K-Means Cluster 1 and GMM Cluster 2, indicating that both algorithms agree on this grouping of customers. However, Clusters 0 and 1 in GMM overlap more significantly, as GMM’s soft clustering allows points to belong to multiple clusters with varying probabilities.

  • For example, K-Means Cluster 0 corresponds perfectly to GMM Cluster 0, suggesting that both algorithms see the same group of customers as forming a distinct cluster. However, GMM's soft clustering means that customers who might fall between Cluster 1 and 0 in K-Means could have shared membership across clusters in GMM.

    Conclusion: The alignment of clusters suggests both algorithms identify core customer segments, but GMM’s flexibility allows it to capture overlapping segments, giving more nuanced insights.

    3. Cluster Characteristics:

  • Both K-Means and GMM identify high-value customers with similar characteristics, but GMM may offer more flexibility in capturing customers who share characteristics with multiple segments. For example, GMM Cluster 3 might contain high-value customers with many credit cards and high average credit limits, while K-Means Cluster 2 could highlight a similar high-value group but force stricter boundaries.

  • Additionally, GMM could help identify customers who transition between groups, such as those who share some traits of both low and high-value customers, due to its probabilistic assignment.

    Conclusion: Both algorithms successfully identify key customer segments (e.g., high-value or low-engagement customers), but GMM’s flexibility gives additional insights into customers who may not fit neatly into a single cluster, offering a more nuanced view of overlapping customer behaviors.

    Overall Insights:

    • K-Means provides a clearer separation of customer groups, making it suitable for applications where strict cluster boundaries are important.
    • GMM allows for a more flexible, probabilistic approach, making it ideal for identifying customers who might exhibit characteristics of multiple clusters or where there is overlap in customer behavior.
    • Both algorithms identify key customer segments, but the choice of which to use depends on whether you prioritize hard or soft clustering and whether the clusters should have equal sizes or reflect the true underlying structure of the data.

# Using Elbow plot to find the value of k

# Trying multiple values of n_clusters
sse = []  # Sum of squared distances

for k in range(1, 10):
    kmedoids = KMedoids(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    kmedoids.fit(data_pca)
    sse.append(kmedoids.inertia_)  # Use inertia attribute to store squared distances

# Plotting the elbow plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.plot(range(1, 10), sse, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Sum of Squared Distances')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal k')
plt.show()

Observation:

The optimal number of clusters (n_components) is typically selected where the curve shows a noticeable "bend" or "elbow." This is the point where the sum of squared distances starts to decrease at a slower rate.

From the plot, we can observe that the elbow occurs at k = 3. This suggests that choosing 3 clusters would be a good balance between minimizing within-cluster variation and avoiding too many clusters.

Key Takeaways:¶

  • Clusters 0 and 1 from both algorithms are perfectly aligned.
  • Clusters 2 and 3 show some degree of misalignment:
    • K-Medoids shifted 3 data points from K-Means cluster 2 to K-Medoids cluster 1.
    • K-Medoids labeled the data points from K-Means cluster 3 as K-Medoids cluster 2 but did not affect their grouping.

Conclusion:¶

The comparison shows that K-Means and K-Medoids largely agree on the cluster assignments, especially for clusters 0 and 1. However, there is some minor discrepancy between cluster 2 and cluster 3, where a small number of data points were assigned differently between the two methods.

When comparing the K-Medoids clustering to the K-Means clustering (as seen in the previous scatterplot), several observations can be made:¶

  1. Cluster Separation:
    • In K-Means, the clusters appear more distinctly separated, with the points forming more compact groups. Particularly, Cluster 2 (green) in K-Means is tightly clustered.
    • In K-Medoids, the separation between clusters is still visible, but there is more overlap between Cluster 0 (green) and Cluster 2 (blue) compared to the K-Means version. The K-Medoids algorithm is more sensitive to the specific points it selects as medoids, leading to a different distribution of clusters.

  1. Cluster Shape and Size:

    • K-Means typically results in spherical clusters since it minimizes the variance within each cluster. The clusters are well-defined and tend to cover areas with similar densities. For example, in K-Means, Cluster 2 (green) occupies a distinct region in the upper right, and Cluster 0 (red) is more compact around the center.
    • In K-Medoids, the clusters are less spherical and may show more varied shapes due to the algorithm's nature of minimizing the sum of pairwise dissimilarities (rather than the sum of squared distances, as in K-Means). This is particularly evident in Cluster 0 (green), which is more spread out compared to K-Means.
    1. Cluster Distribution:
    • In K-Means, the clusters are spread more evenly across the PCA space, especially Cluster 1 (blue) and Cluster 0 (red), which capture different segments of the data.
    • In K-Medoids, the clusters are also distributed across the space, but Cluster 1 (orange) is slightly less separated, and there is some degree of overlap between Cluster 0 and Cluster 2. This suggests that K-Medoids might not be as effective at separating data points that have more complex boundaries.
    1. Sensitivity to Outliers:
    • K-Means is sensitive to outliers since it uses mean values to determine the center of clusters. If an outlier is far from the rest of the data, it can pull the centroid in that direction.
    • K-Medoids is less sensitive to outliers because it selects actual data points as medoids, minimizing the impact of extreme points. This can be beneficial when you want to avoid outliers affecting the clustering result.
    1. Interpretation of Labels:
    • Both algorithms give similar results in terms of the general clustering pattern, but K-Medoids might perform better when there is a need to ensure the clusters are centered around actual data points (medoids) and where the data is non-spherical or contains outliers.
    • K-Means tends to handle well-separated data more effectively by ensuring a clearer division between groups, while K-Medoids can be useful for datasets with irregular structures or noisy data.

    Conclusion: Both algorithms have clustered the data into similar segments in terms of the general pattern. However, K-Means tends to create more compact and distinct clusters, especially for well-separated groups, while K-Medoids shows more flexibility in the shape and placement of clusters, which may be beneficial if the data contains non-uniform distributions or outliers. Based on the visualizations, K-Means seems to offer more defined groupings, but K-Medoids could be preferable for robustness against outliers.

This comparison helps in selecting an appropriate clustering algorithm depending on the nature of the data.

Conclusions and Business Recommendations¶

Conclusions from the Overall Analysis of AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation Dataset:¶

  1. Customer Segmentation:

    • The analysis successfully segmented AllLife Bank's credit card customer base into distinct groups using multiple clustering algorithms such as K-Means, Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM), and K-Medoids.
    • Each clustering method identified similar customer segments, although the algorithms varied in their sensitivity to data points and outliers.
    • The clusters reflect variations in customer behavior based on factors such as credit limit, total credit cards owned, total visits (in-person, online, call center), and customer key (proxy for the customer’s joining time).

  2. High-Value Customers:

    • One cluster consistently identified across all models contains high-value customers with the highest credit limits and most credit cards. These customers visit the bank less frequently in person, preferring online and other channels for engagement.
    • Another cluster represents lower engagement, low credit limits, and fewer credit cards, indicating a lower-value customer base with less interaction across all channels.

  3. Channel Engagement:

    • Different clusters showed clear preferences for certain channels of interaction (in-person visits, online, or calls to customer care). One of the clusters represented a customer group that was more digitally engaged (using online channels) compared to others.
    • Another cluster was dominated by customers who made frequent in-person visits to the bank while maintaining a moderate number of credit cards.

  4. Credit Card Holding Patterns:

    • There is a clear distinction between clusters based on the total number of credit cards customers hold. Some groups held significantly more cards, while others had just a few. The total number of cards seems to correlate with credit limits and the channels they engage with the bank.

  5. Outliers and Irregular Data:

    • The analysis highlighted some outliers or extreme data points that have significantly higher credit limits or visit the bank much more often than the average customer. These outliers may represent either special cases (VIP customers) or irregular data that should be reviewed.

Business Recommendations:¶

  1. Personalized Marketing Campaigns:

    • The insights from the segmentation can help AllLife Bank design personalized marketing campaigns tailored to each customer segment:
      • High-value customers (Cluster with highest credit limit) can be targeted with premium offerings such as higher credit limits, exclusive benefits, and VIP services to maintain their loyalty.
      • Lower engagement customers could be incentivized with offers that encourage them to use the bank's products more frequently, such as promotions on additional credit cards or benefits for increased transactions.

  2. Optimizing Service Delivery:

    • With channel preferences identified, AllLife Bank can optimize service delivery:
      • For digitally engaged customers, investing in upgraded digital channels such as mobile banking apps or online support can enhance their experience.
      • For in-person engaged customers, improving in-branch services with faster processing, better assistance, and personalized interactions could drive further engagement.

  3. Retention and Upselling:

    • The analysis shows a segment with a moderate number of credit cards but frequent engagement (bank visits). This group represents an opportunity for upselling additional financial products or increasing credit limits.
    • By identifying the lower-value customers, the bank can focus on strategies to increase their engagement and expand their product usage, possibly through loyalty programs or educational campaigns about available services.

  4. Risk Management:

    • Customers who engage less frequently and hold fewer credit cards may also pose a higher risk of attrition. Monitoring these segments and proactively engaging with them can help reduce churn and improve customer retention.
    • The outliers (customers with very high credit limits or significantly different behavior patterns) should be reviewed to ensure they are being properly managed from both a marketing and risk perspective.

  5. Enhancing Customer Support:

    • One segment was identified that frequently contacts the bank via phone calls. AllLife Bank can focus on improving call center services for this group by reducing response times and providing more personalized support through phone interactions. Automated systems and better query resolution systems could be implemented to improve their experience.

  6. Long-term Engagement Strategies:

    • Using time-based customer segmentation (Customer Key), AllLife Bank can identify when customers joined and develop long-term engagement strategies for different cohorts. This can include tailored onboarding programs, loyalty schemes, and anniversary-based incentives to increase customer retention and brand loyalty.

In summary, by leveraging the insights from customer segmentation, AllLife Bank can improve market penetration, optimize service delivery, and enhance customer satisfaction through targeted marketing, personalized engagement, and strategic service enhancements.
